Introduction¶

In this notebook I plan to study a movie datased named TMDB. As we will see, this dataset includes movie data starting in the 60s and we will analyze it in different steps.

  1. First, we will download the dataset and analyse its contents
  2. Then, based on our analysis, we will propose some questions to answer
  3. At this point, we will use our recent acquired DataFrame skills to answer those questions
  4. Finally, we will draw some conclussions on our work

Let´s start doing some standard setup work.

# Function that we will use during the exercise to decorate our charts
def decorate(title, xlabel, ylabel, xticks=None, xticklabels=None, yticks=None, yticklabels=None):
    #fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16,9))
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=22)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    ax.set_ylabel(ylabel)  
    if xticks is not None:
        ax.set_xticks(xticks)
    if xticklabels is not None:
        ax.set_xticklabels(xticklabels, rotation=70)
    if yticks is not None:
        ax.set_xticks(yticks)
    if yticklabels is not None:
        ax.set_xticklabels(yticklabels, rotation=70)
    ax.grid(alpha=1)
    sns.set(style="dark")
    fig.tight_layout()

Looking at the describe command, we noticed that the popularity score has a mean value of 0.646 but a max value of 32, which seems a bit strange. Searching the web, we´ve found the way it is calculated and seems that is based in certain user actions like voting over a film or favoriting it (https://developers.themoviedb.org/3/getting-started/popularity).

Being that the case, we have the hypothesis that some films with a huge fan base can have a desproportionate popularity scores against the mean. Also, we think that this score should be higher as the time has passed (more people acting on recent films than in older ones). Let´s plot a scatter graph to test our hypothesis.

Questions¶

After having seen what data we do have, we plan to answer the following questions based on it:

  • What are the distributions revenue, budget (both adjusted for inflation) and vote average?
  • Which are the top movies by revenue (adjusted for inflation) of all time?
    • Which is the most revenue (inflation adjusted) generating movie by decade?
  • How has the market evolved?
    • Has the revenue per movie gone up or down?
    • Is it more profitable to make movies today than in the past?
  • Which movie genres are the most interesting from a profit standpoint?
    • Which movie genres generate more revenue?
    • What are the most profitable genres?
    • Which is the average profit per genre / movie?
  • Which are the top revenue generating actors?
  • Which are the top revenue generating directors?
  • Which are the movies with a higher popularity score?
    • Is there any correlation between Popularity and Vote Average?
  • Which is the best month to release a movie?
    • Number of movie releases by month
    • Revenue (adjusted) by month
    • Comparing number of releases with revenue
  • Correlation questions
    • Are the budget and revenue correlated?
    • Is there any correlation between revenue and runtime?
    • Is there any correlation between popularity and revenue?
    • Can we find any correlation for profit?

Is it more profitable to make movies today than in the past?¶

Until now we´ve been looking just to the revenue adjusted for inflation, but that could be misleading as we can generate a lot of revenue just spending a lot of money. In the following cells we are going to analyze the actual profitability of the market.

In [27]:
# Get the total revenue_adj by year
rev_adj_per_year = df.groupby(['release_year']).revenue_adj.sum()

# Get the total budget_adj by year
budget_adj_per_year = df.groupby(['release_year']).budget_adj.sum()

# Get the profit per year
profit_per_year = rev_adj_per_year - budget_adj_per_year

# Create a dataframe from the group
df_profit_per_year = pd.DataFrame(profit_per_year)
           
    
# Plot

# Variables
chart_title="Adjusted Profit per Movie / Year"
chart_xlabel="Year"
chart_ylabel="Profit"
    
# Plot a line graph
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16,9))
ax.plot(df_profit_per_year)

# Decorate
decorate(chart_title, chart_xlabel, chart_ylabel)

plt.show();

As we can see, even with the revenue per movie going down, the profits of movie production have gone up steadily.

What are the most profitable genres?¶

Knowing wich genres generate more revenue is fine, but we need to look also to the budgets of each one to get a measure of the profitability of them.

In [30]:
# Split genres (this is not needed as we did it in the previous cell, but I´ll leave it here for readability reasons)
genres = (df.genres.str.split('|', expand=True).stack().to_frame(name='genre'))
genres.index = genres.index.droplevel(1)

# Add revenue_adj column grouped by genre
df_grp = pd.DataFrame(genres.join(df['revenue_adj']).groupby('genre').sum())

# Add budget_adj column grouped by genre
df_grp['budget_adj'] = genres.join(df['budget_adj']).groupby('genre').sum()

# Add profit column
df_grp['profit'] = df_grp['revenue_adj'] - df_grp['budget_adj']

# Sort results
df_genres_aux = pd.DataFrame(df_grp.sort_values('profit', ascending=False))

# Plot

#Variables
chart_title="Average profit (adjusted) per movie / genre"
chart_xlabel="Genre"
chart_ylabel="Profit (Adjusted)"
chart_xticks=np.arange(len(df_genres_aux))
chart_xticklabels=df_genres_aux.index

# Plot a bar graph

ax.bar(chart_xticks, df_genres_aux.profit)

# Decorate 
decorate(chart_title, chart_xlabel, chart_ylabel, chart_xticks, chart_xticklabels)

plt.show;

As we are seeing, the top 5 genres by profitability are the same as the top 5 by revenue. The only difference is that Adventure is more profitable than Action, while Action movies generate more revenue overall.

Which is the average profit per genre / movie?¶

We now know the profit per genre in our DataFrame, but there is still a missing piece and is knowing which is the actual profit per movie. To do that, we are going to create a new dataframe grouped by genre, add a profit and movie count columns and then calculate and plot the average profit per genre / movie.

In [31]:
# Split genres (this is not needed as we did it in the previous cell, but I´ll leave it here for readability reasons)
genres = (df.genres.str.split('|', expand=True).stack().to_frame(name='genre'))
genres.index = genres.index.droplevel(1)

# Add revenue_adj column grouped by genre
df_grp = pd.DataFrame(genres.join(df['revenue_adj']).groupby('genre').sum())

# Add budget_adj column grouped by genre
df_grp['budget_adj'] = genres.join(df['budget_adj']).groupby('genre').sum()

# Add a calculated profit per genre column
df_grp['profit'] = df_grp['revenue_adj'] - df_grp['budget_adj']

# Add the count of movies per each genre
df_grp['count'] = genres.join(df).groupby('genre').original_title.count()

# Add one last column with the average profit per movie / genre
df_grp['avg_profit_per_movie'] = df_grp['profit'] / df_grp['count'].astype(float)

# Sort results
df_genres_aux = pd.DataFrame(df_grp.sort_values('avg_profit_per_movie', ascending=False))

# Plot the results

# Variables
chart_title="Average profit (adjusted) per movie / genre"
chart_xlabel="Genre"
chart_ylabel="Avg. Profit (Adjusted)"
chart_xticks=np.arange(len(df_genres_aux))
chart_xticklabels=df_genres_aux.index

# Plot a bar graph
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16,9))
ax.bar(chart_xticks, df_genres_aux.avg_profit_per_movie)

# Decorate
decorate(chart_title, chart_xlabel, chart_ylabel, chart_xticks, chart_xticklabels)

plt.show;

Now we are seeing some interesting data. Looking at the individual profit per movie, Adventure it is still the most profitable one, but Fantasy, Family and Animation appeared in the Top5. In fact, Thriller, Comedy and Drama went down to the 9th, 12th and 14th position in our list.

Comparing number of releases with revenue¶

In [42]:
# Let´s add the dataframes for doing it all in one graph
# https://matplotlib.org/3.1.1/gallery/lines_bars_and_markers/barchart.html#sphx-glr-gallery-lines-bars-and-markers-barchart-py
# https://www.machinelearningplus.com/plots/top-50-matplotlib-visualizations-the-master-plots-python/#41.-Plotting-with-different-scales-using-secondary-Y-axis

x = np.arange(12)
y1 = df_month.groupby('release_month').original_title.count()
y2 = df_month.groupby('release_month').revenue_adj.sum()
width = 0.35

# Plot number of releases by month on the left Y axis
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(16,9))
ax1.bar(x - width/2, y1, width, color='tab:red')

# Plot the revenue (adjusted) by month on the right Y axix
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.bar(x + width/2, y2, width, color='tab:blue')

# Decorate
ax1.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=0, labelsize=12)
ax1.set_ylabel('Number of releases', color='tab:red')
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', rotation=0, labelcolor='tab:red' )
ax1.grid(alpha=1)

ax2.set_ylabel("Revenue (Adjusted)", color='tab:blue')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='tab:blue')
ax2.set_xticks(x)
ax2.set_xticklabels(calendar.month_name[1:13])
ax2.set_title("Movies released by month vs Revenue by month")

sns.set(style="dark")
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show();

Looking at this graph, is pretty evident that the best revenue generating months are June and December. By contrast, January and August seem the worst ones to release a movie.

Can we find any correlation for profit?¶

Finally, just for trying another graph method, we are going to try to find what is correlated with profit. We will use the function heatmap from seaborn to get a correlation matrix of all the different variables in our dataframe.

In [47]:
# Create a new dataframe and add a new calculated profit column
df_aux = df.copy()
df_aux['profit_adj'] = df_aux['revenue_adj'] - df_aux['budget_adj']

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
sns.heatmap(df_aux.corr(), xticklabels=df_aux.corr().columns, yticklabels=df_aux.corr().columns, cmap='GnBu', center=0, annot=True)

# Decorations
plt.title('Correlogram of TMDB', fontsize=22)
plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
plt.show();

With this matrix, it´s pretty easy to see that profit is correlated positively, in addition to budget and revenue, with popularity and vote_count. It also has a weak correlation with runtime (as we´ve found previously) and vote_average, and no correlation at all with the release year.

Conclusions¶

We can extract some conclussions from our analysis, taking into account that our analysis has been only superficial and any finding here stated should probably tested more thoroughly with better statistics methods. Specially, we need to highlight that any finding related with correlation does not imply causation.

Highlights from our analysis:

  • The movie producing business is growing both in terms of productions as in profit. Our dataframe showed us how more and more movies are being produced each year, which is driving down the profit per movie, but for the industry as a whole profit is increasing steadily.
  • The most profitable genres overall are Adventure, Action, Drama, Comedy and Thriller, but if we compute the number of releases in each one, the list changes Adventure, Fantasy, Family, Animation and Action. This seems profitable genres to invest on.
  • If we need to choose a leading actor for our movie we won´t fail with Harrison Ford, Tom Cruise or Tom Hanks.
  • In the director role, we won´t fail with Spielberg, James Cameron or Peter Jackson.
  • The best months to release our movie would be June or December. We should avoid specially January and September.
  • A big budget is not a guarantee, but overall, big budgets seem to generate bigger revenues. Hiring Harrison Ford and Steven Spielberg is not cheap.
  • The runtime of our movie shouldn´t have a big impact on our revenue projections, but as most movies are in the 90 to 120 minutes range, we should have a very good excuse to deviate from those numbers (taking into account that every minute added will increase our costs and reduce our profits).
  • Popularity seems to be correlated with revenue, but as we previously said, we can´t affirma that correlation implies causation.

Limitations¶

I haven´t found any insuperable limitation in the dataset that has prevented me to get the answers to my questions, but here is a list of some of the ones I´ve found during the project:

  • Null values on cast, director and genres column. These affected only to less than 1% of the rows, so I´ve dropped them from the dataset.
  • Popularity max values. Popularity score apparently had some outliers very far from the mean, but after looking at the explanation of that field, I concluded that those were not bad data, it is just how the score is calculated.
  • We do not know what is the format of budget or revenue, but as we were more interested in the dependencies / correlations between them, that did not affect our analysis
  • Runtime has a big number of outliers, but we solved this excluding the bottom and the top 10% of them when we had to deal with any runtime experiment
